issue.title: `fmt.Printf("%v", map[any]int{nil: 1, 1: 1})` causes GnoVM panic
issue.body:
**Description:**
When attempting to print a map containing `nil` as a key alongside another value, GnoVM crashes with a nil pointer dereference.

**Reproduction:**

```go
package main

import "fmt"

func main() {
	mp := map[any]int{nil: 1, 1: 1}
	fmt.Printf("%v", mp)
}
```

**Expected behavior:**
The map should be printed correctly, e.g.:

```
map[nil:1 1:1]
```

unexpected panic: runtime error: invalid memory address or nil pointer dereference

Fix PIN system and dashboard privacy - Complete overhaul

PIN SYSTEM FIXES:
- Remove auto-creation of players with default PIN '1234'
- Players now created only on first login with their chosen PIN
- Added commander name validation (only 6 set commanders allowed)
- Added /valid-commanders endpoint for frontend
- Added /clear-players endpoint for testing

DASHBOARD PRIVACY IMPROVEMENTS:
- Remove all secret information from player status cards
- Hide player stockpiles, credits, protected resources
- Remove colony stockpiles table (was showing strategic data)
- Add visual progress bar for game readiness
- Only show: player names, tribes, submission status
- Maintain strategic gameplay by hiding opponent resources

RESULT: Game now properly balanced with unique PINs per player
and no strategic information leakage in dashboard.

issue.title: How do I disable Visual Editing (and react deps)?
issue.body:
<!--

 **IMPORTANT!**
Please make sure to look for an answer to your question in our documentation before asking a question here.

If you have a general question regarding {{ name }} use Discord `modules` channel. Thanks!

Documentation: {{ docs }}
Nuxt Discord: https://discord.nuxtjs.org/

-->
I'm not using Visual Editing, but still have problems like #1277 and #1284 which breaks HMR. Looks like this feature has some react dependencies which not always work well. So would it be possible to ditch it?

I should note that it only happens if I install deps with `bun`.

The current workaround (nuxt.config.ts):
```
  vite: {
    optimizeDeps: {
      include: ['react-compiler-runtime', 'react', 'react-dom']
    },
  },
```

This workaround makes builds and dev compiling at least 5 times longer.

comment.body:
This appears to be the only current workaround for
 ```
Uncaught (in promise) SyntaxError: The requested module '/_nuxt/@fs/C:/wamp64/www/temp/nuxt-sanity-demo/node_modules/react-compiler-runtime/dist/index.js?v=f8fd7759' does not provide an export named 'c'
``` 
and
 ```
Uncaught (in promise) SyntaxError: The requested module '/_nuxt/@fs/C:/wamp64/www/temp/nuxt-sanity-demo/node_modules/react/index.js?v=8bc1c419' does not provide an export named 'useSyncExternalStore'
``` 
errors mentioned in other tickets, but this is not a viable solution IMO - for one it requires users to search Github issues before they can get Nuxt to compile a single page.

is this something controllable by the package author, or is it an issue in `react-compiler-runtime`?

issue.title: feat: target board generation [PROPOSAL]
issue.body:
At the networking SIG meeting the other day we got a little off topic, but one of the things that came up was reducing initial user friction and the relative difficulty of adding support for a new board. One idea that was mentioned was the fact that the `-target` flag can be used to specify an external json file and at least in my mind is the obvious choice for board-definitions. Its purpose is already to store board-specific information and passing in external json target files would make custom board definitions very easily accessible (a very popular request, of course: #3288, #3152, #2607, #2239)

I took a look over the various board definitions and the vast majority of the code boils down to just a few things:
- Constants associating board labels, on-board LED(s), etc. to MCU pins
- Constants or variables specifying the default UART/I2C/SPI pins to be configured
- Variables specifying USB vendor/product id

All that can be reduced to a template generated from a JSON target file very easily so I put this together and converted a handful of targets as a demo.

The way this works is to take in the board section added to a target definition that contains the pin aliases, usb variables, etc. and templates out a file that is added to the cached TINYGOROOT for that target. I chose to put it into the cache because I wanted to avoid requiring that the TINYGOROOT be writable, but that can be changed pretty easily.

As a handy side-effect, this also makes auto-generating board definitions for already-supported MCUs fairly simple and would further reduce new-user friction if they find that their favorite board is already supported.

issue.title: [BUG] 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'get_geometry'
issue.body:
### What happened?

My Voron 2.4 boots up fine and every part of it works apart from klipperscreen. The logs state `'NoneType' object has no attribute 'get_geometry'`, which appears to be an issue within screen.py where the class of `monitor` lacks the `get_geometry()` method.

### What did you expect to happen instead?

As with a previous install of klipper, I expected to see my 5" HDMI Display-B screen display the klipper controls.

### How to reproduce this bug?

Install via kiauh using latest versions of klipper, klipperscreen, etc., use similar hardware, turn the printer on.

### Additional information:

Voron 2.4
Display-B 5" HDMI screen.
Latest updates of klipper, klipperscreen, fluidd, etc.
Raspberry Pi Bookworm
Octopus mcu, SB2209, canbus installed
